17:["$","div",null,{"className":"prose","children":[["$","h2",null,{"children":"Who Should Choose Which?"}],["$","p",null,{"children":"The ideal user for each platform differs considerably. Grammarly is best suited for grammar checking, professional emails, academic writing, tone detection, making it a strong choice if you fall into any of these categories. Sudowrite, meanwhile, shines for novelists, fiction writers, creative writing, worldbuilding, which means it may be the better pick if your needs align with those use cases.\n\nFounded in 2009, Grammarly describes itself as \"The world's most popular AI writing and grammar checker.\" Sudowrite, established in 2020, positions itself as \"AI writing partner built specifically for fiction authors.\" With 11 years between them, Grammarly brings the maturity and proven track record of a veteran platform, while Sudowrite offers the fresh perspective and modern architecture of a newer entrant."}]]}]
18:["$","div",null,{"className":"verdict-box","children":[["$","h2",null,{"children":"Our Verdict"}],["$","p",null,{"children":"After analyzing all the data, **Grammarly** comes out slightly ahead in this comparison, thanks to more features (6 vs 4), availability of a free plan. However, this does not mean Sudowrite is a poor choice — far from it. Sudowrite excels in its own right, particularly for novelists and fiction writers.\n\nOur recommendation: if you value industry-leading grammar and style checking, go with Grammarly. If purpose-built for fiction with story engine feature matters more to you, Sudowrite is the way to go. Either way, both are solid platforms that have earned their place in the market."}]]}]
